{
  "answer": "**Strīdhana** (woman's separate property) refers to wealth that a woman owns independently, distinct from her husband's or family's shared estate. It is primarily defined across the Smṛti texts as consisting of six categories of gifts received at or around marriage or from close relatives.[^1][^2]\n\nThese are:\n- Gifts given **before the nuptial fire** (e.g., at betrothal).\n- Gifts given **during the bridal procession**.\n- Gifts given **out of affection** (by the husband or others).\n- Gifts received from her **brother**.\n- Gifts received from her **mother**.\n- Gifts received from her **father**.[^1][^2]\n\nSuch property belongs exclusively to the woman during her lifetime and typically passes to her daughters (or their heirs) upon her death. If childless, in approved marriages (e.g., Brāhma, Daiva, etc.), it reverts to her husband; otherwise, to her natal family.[^2] Brothers partitioning paternal inheritance must allocate her share from the mother's estate or paternal gifts intended for her.[^3]\n\nNo other Smṛtis in the corpus (e.g., Yājñavalkya Smṛti) provide additional definitions or expansions beyond this framework, which aligns with inheritance rules emphasizing her autonomy over these assets.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 9, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-71fc56).\n[^2]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-072cc9).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 9, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-8d1a3e).\n[^4]: The term does not appear in Yājñavalkya Smṛti (Chapter 1) or other surveyed Smṛtis (e.g., Viṣṇu, Yama, etc.), confirming Manu's as the foundational account in the corpus.",
